WEBVTT

00:22.860 --> 00:27.220
CHAPTER XII I lay on my straw, but I could not sleep.

00:27.780 --> 00:33.560
I thought of the occurrences of the day. What chiefly struck me was the gentle manners of these

00:33.560 --> 00:39.760
people, and I longed to join them, but dared not. I remembered too well the treatment I had suffered

00:39.760 --> 00:45.700
the night before from the barbarous villagers, and resolved, whatever course of conduct I might

00:45.700 --> 00:51.400
hereafter think it right to pursue, that for the present I would remain quietly in my hobble,

00:51.400 --> 00:57.300
watching and endeavoring to discover the motives which influenced their actions.

00:59.340 --> 01:06.100
The cottagers arose the next morning before the sun. The young woman arranged the cottage and

01:06.100 --> 01:12.160
prepared the food, and the youth departed after the first meal. This day was passed in the same

01:12.160 --> 01:17.460
routine as that which preceded it. The young man was constantly employed out of doors,

01:17.460 --> 01:23.280
and the girl in various laborious occupations within. The old man, whom I soon perceived to

01:23.280 --> 01:29.820
be blind, enjoyed his leisure hours on his instrument or in contemplation. Nothing could

01:29.820 --> 01:35.880
exceed the love and respect which the younger cottagers exhibited towards their venerable

01:35.880 --> 01:42.880
companion. They performed towards him every little office of attention and duty with gentleness,

01:42.880 --> 01:50.320
and he rewarded them with his benevolent smiles. They were not entirely happy. The young man and

01:50.320 --> 01:55.640
his companion often went apart and appeared to weep. I saw no cause for their unhappiness,

01:55.820 --> 02:02.340
but I was deeply affected by it. If such lovely creatures were miserable, it was less strange

02:02.340 --> 02:08.560
that I, an imperfect and solitary being, should be wretched. Yet why were these gentle beings

02:08.560 --> 02:15.300
unhappy? They possessed a delightful house, for which it was in my eyes, and every luxury.

02:15.860 --> 02:19.580
They had a fire to warm them when chill and delicious viands when hungry.

02:20.700 --> 02:25.520
They were dressed in excellent clothes, and still more, they enjoyed one another's company and

02:25.520 --> 02:32.280
speech, interchanging each day looks of affection and kindness. What did their tears imply? Did they

02:32.280 --> 02:39.380
really express pain? I was at first unable to solve these questions, but perpetual attention

02:39.380 --> 02:48.360
and time explained to me many appearances which were first enigmatic. A considerable period

02:48.360 --> 02:53.620
elapsed before I discovered one of the causes of the uneasiness of this amenable family.

02:54.140 --> 02:58.520
It was poverty, and they suffered that evil in a very distressing degree.

02:59.160 --> 03:03.900
Their nourishment consisted entirely of the vegetables of their garden and the milk of one

03:03.900 --> 03:09.460
cow, which gave very little during the winter when its masters could scarcely procure food to

03:09.460 --> 03:15.360
support it. They often, I believe, suffered the pangs of hunger very poignantly, especially the

03:15.360 --> 03:20.720
two younger cottagers, for several times they placed food before the old man when they reserved

03:20.720 --> 03:27.300
none for themselves. This trait of kindness moved me sensibly. I had been accustomed during the night

03:27.300 --> 03:33.360
to steal a part of their store for my own consumption, but when I found that in doing

03:33.360 --> 03:39.680
this I inflicted pain on the cottagers, I abstained and satisfied myself with berries, nuts, and roots,

03:40.020 --> 03:45.700
which I gathered from a neighboring wood. I also discovered another means through which I was

03:45.700 --> 03:51.520
enabled to insist their labors. I found that the youth spent a great part of each day in collecting

03:51.520 --> 03:57.220
wood for the family fire, and during the night I often took his tools, the use of which I quickly

03:57.220 --> 04:03.380
discovered, and brought home firing sufficient for the consumption of several days. I remember

04:03.380 --> 04:08.480
the first time I did this. The young woman, when she opened the door in the morning, appeared greatly

04:08.480 --> 04:14.160
astonished on seeing such a great pile of wood on the outside. She uttered some words in a loud

04:14.160 --> 04:20.980
voice, and the youth joined her, who also expressed surprise. I observed with pleasure that he did not

04:20.980 --> 04:25.580
go into the forest that day, but spent it in repairing the cottage and cultivating the garden.

04:27.680 --> 04:33.500
By degrees I made a discovery of still greater moment. I found that these people possessed the

04:33.500 --> 04:38.060
method of communicating their experience and feelings to one another by articulate sounds.

04:39.160 --> 04:43.000
I perceived that the words they spoke sometimes produced pleasure or pain,

04:43.400 --> 04:49.820
smiles or sadness in the minds and countenances of the hearers. This was indeed a god-like science,

04:49.820 --> 04:55.800
and I ardently desired to become acquainted with it, but I was baffled in every attempt I made for

04:55.800 --> 05:02.400
its purpose. Their pronunciation was quick, and the words they uttered, not having any apparent

05:02.400 --> 05:08.300
connection with visible objects, I was unable to discover any clue by which I could unravel the

05:08.300 --> 05:13.960
mystery of their reference. By great application, however, and after having remained during the

05:13.960 --> 05:18.920
space of several revolutions of the moon in my hobble, I discovered the names that were given

05:18.920 --> 05:25.480
to some of the most familiar objects of discourse. I learned and applied the words fire, milk, bread,

05:25.480 --> 05:31.960
and wood. I learned the names of the cottagers themselves. The youth and his companion had each

05:31.960 --> 05:39.340
of them several names, but the old man had only one, which was father. The girl was called sister,

05:39.420 --> 05:47.160
or Agatha, and the youth Felix, brother, or son. I cannot describe the delight I felt when I learned

05:47.160 --> 05:52.780
the ideas appropriated to each of these sounds and was able to pronounce them. I distinguished

05:52.780 --> 06:00.620
several other words without being able as yet to understand or apply them, such as good, dearest,

06:01.080 --> 06:09.320
unhappy. I spent the winter in this manner. The gentle manners and beauty of the cottagers

06:09.320 --> 06:14.800
greatly endeared them to me. When they were unhappy, I felt depressed. When they rejoiced,

06:14.880 --> 06:21.100
I sympathized in their joys. I saw few human beings besides them, and if any other happened

06:21.100 --> 06:25.820
under the cottage, their harsh manners and rude gait only enhanced me to the superior

06:25.820 --> 06:32.200
accomplishments of my friends. The old man, I could perceive, often endeavored to encourage

06:32.200 --> 06:37.260
his children, as sometimes I found that he called to them to cast off their melancholy.

06:37.700 --> 06:42.480
He would talk in a cheerful accent, and the expression of goodness that bestowed pleasure

06:42.480 --> 06:49.760
upon me. Agatha listened with respect. Her eyes sometimes filled with tears, which she endeavored

06:49.760 --> 06:56.100
to wipe away unperceived, but I found, generally found, that her countenance and tone were more

06:56.100 --> 07:03.200
cheerful after having listened to the exhortations of her father. It was not thus with Felix. He was

07:03.200 --> 07:08.680
always the saddest of the group, and even to my unpracticed senses he appears to have suffered

07:08.680 --> 07:15.900
more deeply than his friends. But if his countenance was more sorrowful, his voice was more cheerful

07:15.900 --> 07:21.240
of that of his sister, especially when he addressed the old man.

07:23.880 --> 07:27.320
I could mention innumerable instances which, although slight,

07:27.960 --> 07:34.360
marked the dispositions of these amiable cottagers. In the midst of poverty and want, Felix carried

07:35.000 --> 07:40.620
with pleasure to his sister the first little white flower that peeped out from beneath the snowy

07:40.620 --> 07:46.980
ground. Early in the morning, before she had risen, he had cleared away the snow that obstructed her

07:46.980 --> 07:52.640
path to the milk house, drew water from the well, and brought the wood from the outhouse,

07:53.160 --> 07:58.540
where, to his perpetual astonishment, he found his store always replenished by an invisible hand.

07:59.520 --> 08:04.920
In the day, I believed, he worked sometimes for a neighboring farmer, because he often went forth

08:04.920 --> 08:10.600
and did not return until dinner, yet brought no wood with him. At other times, he worked in the

08:10.600 --> 08:16.900
garden, but as there was little to do in the frosty season, he read to the old man and Agatha.

08:19.020 --> 08:24.740
This reading had puzzled me extremely at first, but by degrees I discovered that he uttered many

08:24.740 --> 08:30.960
of the same sounds when he read as when he talked. I conjectured, therefore, that he found on the

08:30.960 --> 08:36.540
paper signs for speech which he understood, and I ardently longed to comprehend these also.

08:37.020 --> 08:41.620
But how was that possible when I did not even understand the sounds for which they stood as

08:41.620 --> 08:48.860
signs? I improved, however, sensibly in this science, but not sufficiently to follow any kind

08:48.860 --> 08:55.140
of conversation, although I applied my whole mind to the endeavor, for I easily perceived,

08:55.360 --> 09:02.760
although I eagerly longed to discover myself to the cottagers, I ought not make to the attempt

09:02.760 --> 09:08.640
until I at first become master of their language, which knowledge might enable me to make them

09:08.640 --> 09:15.200
overlook the deformity of my figure, for with this also the contrast perpetually presented to

09:15.200 --> 09:22.560
my eyes had made me acquainted. I admired the perfect forms of my cottagers, their grace,

09:22.740 --> 09:29.620
beauty, and delicate complexions, but how I was terrified when I viewed myself in the transparent

09:29.620 --> 09:36.140
pool. At first I stared back, unable to believe that it was indeed I who reflected in the mirror,

09:36.680 --> 09:42.400
and when I became fully convinced that I was in reality the monster that I am,

09:42.760 --> 09:47.320
I was filled with the bitterest sensations of despondence and mortification.

09:48.320 --> 09:53.980
Alas, I did not yet entirely know the fatal effects of this miserable deformity.

09:54.900 --> 10:00.380
As the sun became warmer and the light of the day longer, the snows vanished, and I beheld

10:01.060 --> 10:07.220
the bare trees and black earth. From this time Felix was more employed, and the heart-moving

10:07.220 --> 10:14.420
indications of impending famine disappeared. Their food, after which I found, was coarse,

10:15.060 --> 10:20.620
but it was wholesome, and they procured a sufficiency of it. Several new kinds of plants

10:20.620 --> 10:25.660
sprang up in the garden, which they dressed, and these signs of comfort increased daily

10:25.660 --> 10:33.640
as the season advanced. The old man, leaning on his son, walked each day at noon when it did not

10:33.640 --> 10:40.140
rain, and I found it was called when the heavens poured forth its waters. This frequently took

10:40.140 --> 10:45.460
place, but a high wind quickly dried the earth, and the season became far more pleasant than it

10:45.460 --> 10:51.280
had been. My mode of life and my hobble was uniform. During the morning I attended the

10:51.280 --> 10:56.160
motions of the cottagers, and when they were dispersed in various occupations I slept.

10:56.700 --> 11:02.040
The remainder of the day was spent in observing my friends. When they had retired to rest,

11:02.100 --> 11:07.680
if there was any moon or the night was starlight, I went to the woods and collected my own food

11:07.680 --> 11:13.740
and fuel for the cottage. When I returned as often as it was necessary, I cleared their path

11:13.740 --> 11:20.560
the snow and performed those offices that I had seen done by Felix. I afterwards found that these

11:20.560 --> 11:26.560
labors, performed by an invisible hand, greatly astonished them, and once or twice I heard them

11:26.560 --> 11:32.700
on these occasions utter the words, good spirit, wonderful, but I did not then understand the

11:33.560 --> 11:40.620
signification of these terms. My thoughts now become more active, and I long to discover the

11:40.620 --> 11:46.200
motives and feelings of these lovely creatures. I was inquisitive to know why Felix appeared so

11:46.200 --> 11:52.900
miserable and Agatha so sad. I thought, foolish wrench, that it might be in my power to restore

11:52.900 --> 11:59.100
happiness to these deserving people. When I slept or was absent, the forms of the venerable blind

11:59.100 --> 12:06.340
father, the gentle Agatha, and the excellent Felix flitted before me. I looked upon them as superior

12:06.340 --> 12:11.980
beings who would be the arbiters of my future destiny. I formed in my imagination a thousand

12:11.980 --> 12:18.320
pictures of presenting myself to them and their gentle reception of me. I imagined that they would

12:18.320 --> 12:24.520
be disgusted until, by my gentle demeanor and conciliating words, I should first win their favor

12:24.520 --> 12:31.520
and afterwards their love. These thoughts exhilarated me and led me to apply with fresh

12:31.520 --> 12:38.500
to the acquiring the art of language. My organs were indeed harsh but supple, and although my

12:38.500 --> 12:44.480
voice was very unlike the soft music of their tones, yet I pronounced such words as I understood

12:44.480 --> 12:52.500
with tolerable ease. It was as the ass and the lap dog, yet surely the gentle ass whose intentions

12:52.500 --> 13:01.400
were affectionate, although his manners were rude, deserved better treatment than blows and excretion.

13:02.080 --> 13:08.820
The pleasant showers and gentle warmth of spring greatly altered the aspect of the earth. Men who

13:08.820 --> 13:14.580
before this change seemed to have been hid in caves dispersed themselves and were employed in

13:14.580 --> 13:20.360
various arts of cultivation. The birds sang in more cheerful tones and the leaves began to bud

13:20.360 --> 13:27.360
forth on the trees. Happy, happy earth. Fit habitation for gods, which so short a time before

13:27.360 --> 13:34.400
was bleak, damp, and unwholesome. My spirits were elevated by the enhancing appearance of nature.

13:35.160 --> 13:38.520
The past was blotted from my memory, the present was tranquil,

13:39.100 --> 13:45.600
and the future guided by bright rays of hope and anticipations of joy. End of chapter 12.

